		<div id="comment_body_64370856"><p>PCIe 3 stood for 7 years, then we started getting doubling every 2 or 3 years after PCIe 4 happened.</p><p>However, PCIe Gen 5 is still waiting for a lot of devices to come along, most devices decided PCIe4 was plenty fast to keep up with them, and haven't bothered targeting Gen5.</p><p>which means multiple integrated devices like 10G networking, WiFi 7, USB 4, and Thunderbolt 4</p><p>PCIe limitations were not standing in the way of any of that. You could have saturated concurrent use of two maxed out USB4 devices, unachievable<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

